# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: protein-design-computational
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] A **coiled coil** is a structural motif in proteins in which two to seven alpha-helices are coiled together like the strands of a rope.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] (Dimers and trimers are the most common types.) They have been found in roughly 5-10% of proteins and have a variety of functions.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] They are one of the most widespread motifs found in protein-protein interactions.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] To aid protein study, several tools have been developed to predict coiled-coils in protein structures.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Many coiled coil-type proteins are involved in important biological functions, such as the regulation of gene expression — e.g., transcription factors.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Notable examples are the oncoproteins c-Fos and c-Jun, as well as the muscle protein tropomyosin.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The possibility of coiled coils for α-keratin was initially somewhat controversial.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Linus Pauling and Francis Crick independently came to the conclusion that this was possible at about the same time.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] In the summer of 1952, Pauling visited the laboratory in England where Crick worked.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Pauling and Crick met and spoke about various topics; at one point, Crick asked whether Pauling had considered *coiled coils* (a term Crick came up with), to which Pauling said he had.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Upon returning to the United States, Pauling resumed research on the topic.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] He concluded that coiled coils exist, and submitted a lengthy manuscript to the journal *Nature* in October.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Pauling's son Peter Pauling worked at the same lab as Crick, and mentioned the report to him.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Crick believed that Pauling had stolen his idea, and submitted a shorter note to *Nature* a few days after Pauling's manuscript arrived.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Eventually, after some controversy and frequent correspondences, Crick's lab declared that the idea had been reached independently by both researchers, and that no intellectual theft had occurred.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] In his note (which was published first due to its shorter length), Crick proposed the *coiled coil* and as well as mathematical methods for determining their structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Remarkably, this was soon after the structure of the alpha helix was suggested in 1951 by Linus Pauling and coworkers.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] These studies were published in the absence of knowledge of a keratin sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The first keratin sequences were determined by Hanukoglu and Fuchs in 1982.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Based on sequence and secondary structure prediction analyses identified the coiled-coil domains of keratins.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] These models have been confirmed by structural analyses of coiled-coil domains of keratins.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Coiled coils usually contain a repeated pattern, *hxxhcxc*, of hydrophobic (*h*) and charged (*c*) amino-acid residues, referred to as a heptad repeat.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The positions in the heptad repeat are usually labeled *abcdefg*, where *a* and *d* are the hydrophobic positions, often being occupied by isoleucine, leucine, or valine.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Folding a sequence with this repeating pattern into an alpha-helical secondary structure causes the hydrophobic residues to be presented as a 'stripe' that coils gently around the helix in left-handed fashion, forming an amphipathic structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The most favorable way for two such helices to arrange themselves in the water-filled environment of the cytoplasm is to wrap the hydrophobic strands against each other sandwiched between the hydrophilic amino acids.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Thus, it is the burial of hydrophobic surfaces that provides the thermodynamic driving force for the oligomerization.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The packing in a coiled-coil interface is exceptionally tight, with almost complete van der Waals contact between the side-chains of the *a* and *d* residues.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] This tight packing was originally predicted by Francis Crick in 1952 and is referred to as knobs into holes packing.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The α-helices may be parallel or anti-parallel, and usually adopt a *left-handed* super-coil (Figure 1).
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Although disfavored, a few *right-handed* coiled coils have also been observed in nature and in designed proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] As coiled-coil domains are common among a significant amount of proteins in a wide variety of protein families, they help proteins fulfill various functions in the cell.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Their primary feature is to facilitate protein-protein interaction and keep proteins or domains interlocked.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] This feature corresponds to several subfunctions, including membrane fusion, molecular spacing, oligomerization tags, vesicle movement, aid in movement proteins, cell structure, and more.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] A coiled coil domain plays a role in human immunodeficiency virus type 1 (HIV-1) infection.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Viral entry into CD4-positive cells commences when three subunits of a glycoprotein 120 (gp120) bind to CD4 receptor and a coreceptor.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Glycoprotein gp120 is closely associated with a trimer of gp41 via van der Waals interactions.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Eventually, the gp41 N-terminal fusion peptide sequence anchors into the host cell.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] A spring-loaded mechanism is responsible for bringing the viral and cell membranes in close enough proximity that they will fuse.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The origin of the spring-loaded mechanism lies within the exposed gp41, which contains two consecutive heptad repeats (HR1 and HR2) following the fusion peptide at the N terminus of the protein.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] HR1 forms a parallel, trimeric coiled coil onto which HR2 region coils, forming the trimer-of-hairpins (or six-helix bundle) structure, thereby facilitating membrane fusion through bringing the membranes close to each other.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The virus then enters the cell and begins its replication.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Recently, inhibitors derived from HR2 such as Fuzeon (DP178, T-20) that bind to the HR1 region on gp41 have been developed.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] However, peptides derived from HR1 have little viral inhibition efficacy due to the propensity for these peptides to aggregate in solution.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Chimeras of these HR1-derived peptides with GCN4 leucine zippers have been developed and have shown to be more active than Fuzeon.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Human immunodeficiency virus type 2 has a membrane envelope glycoprotein with similar structure to HIV-1 gp41, but containing substitutions for a glycine amino acid residue in the coiled coil domain that may impact trimer stability.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The proteins SNAP-25, synaptobrevin, and syntaxin-1 have alpha-helices which interact with each other to form a coiled-coil SNARE complex.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Zippering the domains together provides the necessary energy for vesicle fusion to occur.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The coiled-coil motif may also act as a spacer between two objects within a cell.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The lengths of these molecular spacer coiled-coil domains are highly conserved.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The purpose of these molecular spacers may be to separate protein domains, thus keeping them from interacting, or to separate vesicles within the cell to mediate vesicle transport.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] An example of this first purpose is Omp‐α found in *T. maritima*.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Other proteins keep vesicles apart, such as p115, giantin, and GM130 which interact with each other via coiled-coil motifs and act as a tether between the Golgi and a nearby vesicle.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The family of proteins related to this activity of tethering vesicles to the Golgi are known as golgins.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Finally, there are several proteins with coiled-coil domains involved in the kinetochore, which keeps chromosomes separated during cell division.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] These proteins include Ndc-80, and Nuf2p.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Related proteins interact with microtubules during cell division, of which mutation leads to cell death.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Because of their specific interaction coiled coils can be used as "tags" to stabilize or enforce a specific oligomerization state.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] A coiled coil interaction has been observed to drive the oligomerization of the BBS2 and BBS7 subunits of the BBSome.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Because coiled-coils generally interact with other coiled coils, they are found in proteins which are required to form dimers or tetramers with more copies of themselves.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Because of their ability in driving protein oligomerization, they have also been studied in their use in forming synthetic nanostructures.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The general problem of deciding on the folded structure of a protein when given the amino acid sequence (the so-called protein folding problem) has only been solved partially.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] However, the coiled coil is one of a relatively small number of folding motifs for which the relationships between the sequence and the final folded structure are comparatively well understood.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Harbury *et al.* performed a landmark study using an archetypal coiled coil, GCN4, in which rules that govern the way that peptide sequence affects the oligomeric state (that is, the number of alpha-helices in the final assembly) were established.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] When the amino acids in the *a* and *d* positions were changed from I at *a* and L at *d* to I at *a* and I at *d*, a trimeric (three alpha-helices) coiled coil was formed.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Furthermore, switching the positions of L to *a* and I to *d* resulted in the formation of a tetrameric (four alpha-helices) coiled coil.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] These represent a set of rules for the determination of coiled coil oligomeric states and allows scientists to effectively "dial-in" the oligomerization behavior.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Another aspect of coiled coil assembly that is relatively well understood, at least in the case of dimeric coiled coils, is that placing a polar residue (in particular asparagine, N) at opposing *a* positions forces parallel assembly of the coiled coil.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] This effect is due to a self-complementary hydrogen bonding between these residues, which would go unsatisfied if an N were paired with, for instance, an L on the opposing helix.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] It was recently demonstrated by Peacock, Pikramenou and co-workers that coiled coils may be self-assembled using lanthanide(III) ions as a template, thus producing novel imaging agents.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Coiled-coil motifs have been experimented on as possible building block for nanostructures, in part because of their simple design and wide range of function based primarily on facilitating protein-protein interaction.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Simple guidelines for de novo synthesis of new proteins containing coiled-coil domains have led to many applications being hypothesized, including drug delivery, regenerating tissue, protein origami, and much more.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] In regards to drug delivery, coiled-coil domains would help overcome some of the hazards of chemotherapeutic drugs, by keeping them from leaking into healthy tissue as they are transported to their target.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Coiled-coil domains can be made to bind to specific proteins or cell surface markers, allowing for more precise targeting in drug delivery.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Other functions would be to help store and transport drugs within the body that would otherwise degrade rapidly, by creating nanotubes and other structure svia the interlocking of coiled-coil motifs.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] By utilizing the function of oligomerization of proteins via coiled-coil domains, antigen display can be amplified in vaccines, increasing their effectiveness.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] The oligomerization of coiled-coil motifs allows for the creation of protein origami and protein building blocks.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Metal-ligand interactions, covalent bonds, and ionic interactions have been studied to manipulate possible coiled-coil interactions in this field of study.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Several different nanostructures can be made by combining coiled-coil motifs such that they are self-assembling building blocks.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] However, several difficulties remain with stability.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] Using peptides with coiled-coil motifs for scaffolding has made it easier to create 3D structures for cell culturing.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] 3D hydrogels can be made with these peptides, and then cells may be loaded into the matrix.
[src:protein-design-computational/coiled-coil] This has applications in the study of tissue, tissue engineering, and more.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] In computational biology, ***de novo* protein structure prediction** refers to an algorithmic process by which protein tertiary structure is predicted from its amino acid primary sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] The problem itself has occupied leading scientists for decades while still remaining unsolved.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] According to Science, the problem remains one of the top 125 outstanding issues in modern science.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] At present, some of the most successful methods have a reasonable probability of predicting the folds of small, single-domain proteins within 1.5 angstroms over the entire structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Currently, the gap between known protein sequences and confirmed protein structures is immense.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] At the beginning of 2008, only about 1% of the sequences listed in the UniProtKB database corresponded to structures in the Protein Data Bank (PDB), leaving a gap between sequence and structure of approximately five million.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Experimental techniques for determining tertiary structure have faced serious bottlenecks in their ability to determine structures for particular proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] For example, whereas X-ray crystallography has been successful in crystallizing approximately 80,000 cytosolic proteins, it has been far less successful in crystallizing membrane proteins – approximately 280.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] In light of experimental limitations, devising efficient computer programs to close the gap between known sequence and structure is believed to be the only feasible option.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] A general paradigm for *de novo* prediction involves sampling conformation space, guided by scoring functions and other sequence-dependent biases such that a large set of candidate (“decoy") structures are generated.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Native-like conformations are then selected from these decoys using scoring functions as well as conformer clustering.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] High-resolution refinement is sometimes used as a final step to fine-tune native-like structures.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] There are two major classes of scoring functions.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Physics-based functions are based on mathematical models describing aspects of the known physics of molecular interaction.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Knowledge-based functions are formed with statistical models capturing aspects of the properties of native protein conformations.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Several lines of evidence have been presented in favor of the notion that primary protein sequence contains all the information required for overall three-dimensional protein structure, making the idea of a de novo protein prediction possible.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] First, proteins with different functions usually have different amino acid sequences.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Second, several different human diseases, such as Duchenne muscular dystrophy, can be linked to loss of protein function resulting from a change in just a single amino acid in the primary sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Third, proteins with similar functions across many different species often have similar amino acid sequences.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Ubiquitin, for example, is a protein involved in regulating the degradation of other proteins; its amino acid sequence is nearly identical in species as far separated as *Drosophila melanogaster* and *Homo sapiens*.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Fourth, by thought experiment, one can deduce that protein folding must not be a completely random process and that information necessary for folding must be encoded within the primary structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] For example, if we assume that each of 100 amino acid residues within a small polypeptide could take up 10 different conformations on average, giving 10^100 different conformations for the polypeptide.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] If one possible conformation was tested every 10^-13 second, then it would take about 10^77 years to sample all possible conformations.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] However, proteins are properly folded within the body on short timescales all the time, meaning that the process cannot be random and, thus, can potentially be modeled.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] One of the strongest lines of evidence for the supposition that all the relevant information needed to encode protein tertiary structure is found in the primary sequence was demonstrated in the 1950s by Christian Anfinsen.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] In a classic experiment, he showed that ribonuclease A could be entirely denatured by being submerged in a solution of urea (to disrupt stabilizing hydrophobic bonds) in the presence of a reducing agent (to cleave stabilizing disulfide bonds).
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Upon removal of the protein from this environment, the denatured and functionless ribonuclease protein spontaneously recoiled and regained function, demonstrating that protein tertiary structure is encoded in the primary amino acid sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Had the protein reformed randomly, over one-hundred different combinations of four disulfide bonds could have formed.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] However, in the majority of cases proteins will require the presence of molecular chaperons within the cell for proper folding.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] The overall shape of a protein may be encoded in its amino acid structure, but its folding may depend on chaperons to assist in folding.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] De novo conformation predictors usually function by producing candidate conformations (decoys) and then choosing amongst them based on their thermodynamic stability and energy state.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] De novo programs will search three dimensional space and, in the process, produce candidate protein conformations.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] As a protein approaches its correctly folded, native state, entropy and free energy will decrease.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Using this information, de novo predictors can discriminate amongst decoys.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Specifically, de novo programs will select possible conformations with lower free energies – which are more likely to be correct than those structures with higher free energies.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] However, some *de novo* methods work by first enumerating through the entire conformational space using a simplified representation of a protein structure, and then select the ones that are most likely to be native-like.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] An example of this approach is one based on representing protein folds using tetrahedral lattices and building all atoms models on top of all possible conformations obtained using the tetrahedral representation.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] This approach was used successfully at CASP3 to predict a protein fold whose topology had not been observed before by Michael Levitt's team.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] By developing the QUARK program, Xu and Zhang showed that ab initio structure of some proteins can be successfully constructed through a knowledge-based force field .
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] If a protein of known tertiary structure shares at least 30% of its sequence with a potential homolog of undetermined structure, comparative methods that overlay the putative unknown structure with the known can be utilized to predict the likely structure of the unknown.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] However, below this threshold three other classes of strategy are used to determine possible structure from an initial model: ab initio protein prediction, fold recognition, and threading.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] **Fold Prediction:** In fold recognition strategies, a prediction of secondary structure is first made and then compared to either a library of known protein folds, such as CATH or SCOP, or what is known as a "periodic table" of possible secondary structure forms.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] A confidence score is then assigned to likely matches.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] **Threading:** In threading strategies, the fold recognition technique is expanded further.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] In this process, empirically based energy functions for the interaction of residue pairs are used to place the unknown protein onto a putative backbone as a best fit, accommodating gaps where appropriate.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] The best interactions are then accentuated in order to discriminate amongst potential decoys and to predict the most likely conformation.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] The goal of both fold and threading strategies is to ascertain whether a fold in an unknown protein is similar to a domain in a known one deposited in a database, such as the protein databank (PDB).
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] This is in contrast to de novo (ab initio) methods where structure is determined using a physics-base approach en lieu of comparing folds in the protein to structures in a data base.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] A major limitation of de novo protein prediction methods is the extraordinary amount of computer time required to successfully solve for the native conformation of a protein.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Distributed methods, such as Rosetta@home, have attempted to ameliorate this by recruiting individuals who then volunteer idle home computer time in order to process data.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Even these methods face challenges, however.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] For example, a distributed method was utilized by a team of researchers at the University of Washington and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute to predict the tertiary structure of the protein T0283 from its amino acid sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] In a blind test comparing the accuracy of this distributed technique with the experimentally confirmed structure deposited within the Protein Databank (PDB), the predictor produced excellent agreement with the deposited structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] However, the time and number of computers required for this feat was enormous – almost two years and approximately 70,000 home computers, respectively.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] One method proposed to overcome such limitations involves the use of Markov models (see Markov chain Monte Carlo).
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] One possibility is that such models could be constructed in order to assist with free energy computation and protein structure prediction, perhaps by refining computational simulations.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Another way of circumventing the computational power limitations is using coarse-grained modeling.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Coarse-grained protein models allow for de novo structure prediction of small proteins, or large protein fragments, in a short computational time.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Another limitation of protein structure prediction software concerns a specific class of proteins, namely *de novo* proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Structure prediction software such as AlphaFold rely on co-evolutionary data derived from multiple sequence alignment (MSA) and homologous protein sequences to predict structures of proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] However, per definition, *de novo* proteins lack homologous sequences, as they are evolutionarily new.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Thus, structure prediction software which relies on such homology can be expected to perform poorly in predicting structures of *de novo* proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] To improve accuracy of structure prediction for *de novo* proteins, new softwares have been developed.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] Namely, ESMFold is a newly developed large language model (LLM) for the prediction of protein structures based solely on their amino acid sequences.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] It can predict a 3D structure of a protein with atomic-level resolution with an input of a single amino acid sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] “Progress for all variants of computational protein structure prediction methods is assessed in the biannual, community wide Critical Assessment of Protein Structure Prediction (CASP) experiments.
[src:protein-design-computational/de-novo-protein-structure-prediction] In the CASP experiments, research groups are invited to apply their prediction methods to amino acid sequences for which the native structure is not known but to be determined and to be published soon.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] David Baker, a protein research scientist at the University of Washington, founded the Foldit project.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Before starting the project, Baker and his laboratory coworkers relied on another research project named Rosetta to predict the native structures of various proteins using special computer protein structure prediction algorithms.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Rosetta was eventually extended to use the power of distributed computing: The Rosetta@home program was made available for public download, and displayed its protein-folding progress as a screensaver.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Its results were sent to a central server for verification.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Some Rosetta@home users became frustrated when they saw ways to solve protein structures, but could not interact with the program.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Many of the same people who created Rosetta@home worked on Foldit.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] The public beta version was released in May 2008 and has 240,000 registered players.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Since 2008, Foldit has participated in Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction (CASP) experiments, submitting its best solutions to targets based on unknown protein structures.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] CASP is an international program to assess methods of protein structure prediction and identify those that are most productive.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Protein structure prediction is important in several fields of science, including bioinformatics, molecular biology, and medicine.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Identifying natural proteins' structural configurations enables scientists to understand them better.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] This can lead to creating novel proteins by design, advances in treating disease, and solutions for other real-world problems such as invasive species, waste, and pollution.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] The process by which living beings create the primary structure of proteins, protein biosynthesis, is reasonably well understood, as is the means by which proteins are encoded as DNA.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] However, determining how a given protein's primary structure becomes a functioning three-dimensional structure, how the molecule *folds*, is more difficult.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] The general process is understood, but predicting a protein's eventual, functioning structure is computationally demanding.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Similarly to Rosetta@home, Foldit is a means to discover native protein structures faster through distributed computing.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] However, Foldit has a greater emphasis on community collaboration through its forums, where users can collaborate on certain folds.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Furthermore, Foldit's crowdsourced approach places a greater emphasis on the user.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Foldit's virtual interaction and gamification create a unique and innovative environment with the potential to greatly advance protein folding research.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Foldit attempts to apply the human brain's three-dimensional pattern matching and spatial reasoning abilities to help solve the problem of protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] 2016 puzzles are based on well-understood proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] By analysing how humans intuitively approach these puzzles, researchers hope to improve the algorithms used by protein-folding software.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Foldit includes a series of tutorials where users manipulate simple protein-like structures and a periodically updated set of puzzles based on real proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] It shows a graphical representation of each protein which users can manipulate using a set of tools.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Foldit's developers wanted to attract as many people as possible to the cause of protein folding.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] So, rather than only building a useful science tool, they used gamification (the inclusion of gaming elements) to make Foldit appealing and engaging to the general public.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] As a protein structure is modified, a *score* is calculated based on how well-folded the protein is, and a list of high scores for each puzzle is maintained.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Foldit users may create and join groups, and members of groups can share puzzle solutions.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Groups have been found to be useful in training new players.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] A separate list of group high scores is maintained, as well as two leaderboards for groups and individuals.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Results from Foldit have been included in a number of scientific publications.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Foldit players have been cited collectively as "Foldit players" or "Players, F." in some cases.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Individual players have also been listed as authors on at least one paper, and on four related Protein Data Bank depositions.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Foldit's toolbox is mainly for the design of protein molecules.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] The game's creator announced the plan to add, by 2013, the chemical building blocks of organic subcomponents to enable players to design small molecules.
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] The small molecule design system termed *Drugit* was tested on the Von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL).
[src:protein-design-computational/foldit] Results of the VHL experiment were presented in a March 2023 preprint paper and at an August 2023 American Chemical Society conference session.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Rational protein design dates back to the mid-1970s.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Recently, however, there were numerous examples of successful rational design of water-soluble and even transmembrane peptides and proteins, in part due to a better understanding of different factors contributing to protein structure stability and development of better computational methods.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The goal in rational protein design is to predict amino acid sequences that will fold to a specific protein structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Although the number of possible protein sequences is vast, growing exponentially with the size of the protein chain, only a subset of them will fold reliably and quickly to one native state.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein design involves identifying novel sequences within this subset.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The native state of a protein is the conformational free energy minimum for the chain.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, protein design is the search for sequences that have the chosen structure as a free energy minimum.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In a sense, it is the reverse of protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In design, a tertiary structure is specified, and a sequence that will fold to it is identified.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Hence, it is also termed *inverse folding*.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein design is then an optimization problem: using some scoring criteria, an optimized sequence that will fold to the desired structure is chosen.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] When the first proteins were rationally designed during the 1970s and 1980s, the sequence for these was optimized manually based on analyses of other known proteins, the sequence composition, amino acid charges, and the geometry of the desired structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The first designed proteins are attributed to Bernd Gutte, who designed a reduced version of a known catalyst, bovine ribonuclease, and tertiary structures consisting of beta-sheets and alpha-helices, including a binder of DDT.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Urry and colleagues later designed elastin-like fibrous peptides based on rules on sequence composition.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Richardson and coworkers designed a 79-residue protein with no sequence homology to a known protein.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In the 1990s, the advent of powerful computers, libraries of amino acid conformations, and force fields developed mainly for molecular dynamics simulations enabled the development of structure-based computational protein design tools.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Following the development of these computational tools, great success has been achieved over the last 30 years in protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The first protein successfully designed completely *de novo* was done by Stephen Mayo and coworkers in 1997, and, shortly after, in 1999 Peter S.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Kim and coworkers designed dimers, trimers, and tetramers of unnatural right-handed coiled coils.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In 2003, David Baker's laboratory designed a full protein to a fold never seen before in nature.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Later, in 2008, Baker's group computationally designed enzymes for two different reactions.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In 2010, one of the most powerful broadly neutralizing antibodies was isolated from patient serum using a computationally designed protein probe.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In 2024, Baker received one half of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his advancement of computational protein design, with the other half being shared by Demis Hassabis and John Jumper of Deepmind for protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Due to these and other successes (e.g., see examples below), protein design has become one of the most important tools available for protein engineering.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] There is great hope that the design of new proteins, small and large, will have uses in biomedicine and bioengineering.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein design programs use computer models of the molecular forces that drive proteins in *in vivo* environments.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In order to make the problem tractable, these forces are simplified by protein design models.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein function is heavily dependent on protein structure, and rational protein design uses this relationship to design function by designing proteins that have a target structure or fold.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, by definition, in rational protein design the target structure or ensemble of structures must be known beforehand.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] This contrasts with other forms of protein engineering, such as directed evolution, where a variety of methods are used to find proteins that achieve a specific function, and with protein structure prediction where the sequence is known, but the structure is unknown.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Most often, the target structure is based on a known structure of another protein.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] However, novel folds not seen in nature have been made increasingly possible.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Kim and coworkers designed trimers and tetramers of unnatural coiled coils, which had not been seen before in nature.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The protein Top7, developed in David Baker's lab, was designed completely using protein design algorithms, to a completely novel fold.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] More recently, Baker and coworkers developed a series of principles to design ideal globular-protein structures based on protein folding funnels that bridge between secondary structure prediction and tertiary structures.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] These principles, which build on both protein structure prediction and protein design, were used to design five different novel protein topologies.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In rational protein design, proteins can be redesigned from the sequence and structure of a known protein, or completely from scratch in *de novo* protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In protein redesign, most of the residues in the sequence are maintained as their wild-type amino-acid while a few are allowed to mutate.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In *de novo* design, the entire sequence is designed anew, based on no prior sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Both *de novo* designs and protein redesigns can establish rules on the sequence space: the specific amino acids that are allowed at each mutable residue position.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] For example, the composition of the surface of the RSC3 probe to select HIV-broadly neutralizing antibodies was restricted based on evolutionary data and charge balancing.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Many of the earliest attempts on protein design were heavily based on empiric *rules* on the sequence space.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Moreover, the design of fibrous proteins usually follows strict rules on the sequence space.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Collagen-based designed proteins, for example, are often composed of Gly-Pro-X repeating patterns.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The advent of computational techniques allows designing proteins with no human intervention in sequence selection.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In protein design, the target structure (or structures) of the protein are known.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] However, a rational protein design approach must model some *flexibility* on the target structure in order to increase the number of sequences that can be designed for that structure and to minimize the chance of a sequence folding to a different structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] For example, in a protein redesign of one small amino acid (such as alanine) in the tightly packed core of a protein, very few mutants would be predicted by a rational design approach to fold to the target structure, if the surrounding side-chains are not allowed to be repacked.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, an essential parameter of any design process is the amount of flexibility allowed for both the side-chains and the backbone.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In the simplest models, the protein backbone is kept rigid while some of the protein side-chains are allowed to change conformations.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] However, side-chains can have many degrees of freedom in their bond lengths, bond angles, and *χ* dihedral angles.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] To simplify this space, protein design methods use rotamer libraries that assume ideal values for bond lengths and bond angles, while restricting *χ* dihedral angles to a few frequently observed low-energy conformations termed rotamers.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Rotamer libraries are derived from the statistical analysis of many protein structures.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Backbone-independent rotamer libraries describe all rotamers.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Backbone-dependent rotamer libraries, in contrast, describe the rotamers as how likely they are to appear depending on the protein backbone arrangement around the side chain.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Most protein design programs use one conformation (e.g., the modal value for rotamer dihedrals in space) or several points in the region described by the rotamer; the OSPREY protein design program, in contrast, models the entire continuous region.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Although rational protein design must preserve the general backbone fold a protein, allowing some backbone flexibility can significantly increase the number of sequences that fold to the structure while maintaining the general fold of the protein.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Backbone flexibility is especially important in protein redesign because sequence mutations often result in small changes to the backbone structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Moreover, backbone flexibility can be essential for more advanced applications of protein design, such as binding prediction and enzyme design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Some models of protein design backbone flexibility include small and continuous global backbone movements, discrete backbone samples around the target fold, backrub motions, and protein loop flexibility.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Rational protein design techniques must be able to discriminate sequences that will be stable under the target fold from those that would prefer other low-energy competing states.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, protein design requires accurate energy functions that can rank and score sequences by how well they fold to the target structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] At the same time, however, these energy functions must consider the computational challenges behind protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] One of the most challenging requirements for successful design is an energy function that is both accurate and simple for computational calculations.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The most accurate energy functions are those based on quantum mechanical simulations.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] However, such simulations are too slow and typically impractical for protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Instead, many protein design algorithms use either physics-based energy functions adapted from molecular mechanics simulation programs, knowledge based energy-functions, or a hybrid mix of both.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The trend has been toward using more physics-based potential energy functions.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Physics-based energy functions, such as AMBER and CHARMM, are typically derived from quantum mechanical simulations, and experimental data from thermodynamics, crystallography, and spectroscopy.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] These energy functions typically simplify physical energy function and make them pairwise decomposable, meaning that the total energy of a protein conformation can be calculated by adding the pairwise energy between each atom pair, which makes them attractive for optimization algorithms.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Physics-based energy functions typically model an attractive-repulsive Lennard-Jones term between atoms and a pairwise electrostatics coulombic term between non-bonded atoms.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Statistical potentials, in contrast to physics-based potentials, have the advantage of being fast to compute, of accounting implicitly of complex effects and being less sensitive to small changes in the protein structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] These energy functions are based on deriving energy values from frequency of appearance on a structural database.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein design, however, has requirements that can sometimes be limited in molecular mechanics force-fields.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Molecular mechanics force-fields, which have been used mostly in molecular dynamics simulations, are optimized for the simulation of single sequences, but protein design searches through many conformations of many sequences.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, molecular mechanics force-fields must be tailored for protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In practice, protein design energy functions often incorporate both statistical terms and physics-based terms.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] For example, the Rosetta energy function, one of the most-used energy functions, incorporates physics-based energy terms originating in the CHARMM energy function, and statistical energy terms, such as rotamer probability and knowledge-based electrostatics.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Typically, energy functions are highly customized between laboratories, and specifically tailored for every design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Water makes up most of the molecules surrounding proteins and is the main driver of protein structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, modeling the interaction between water and protein is vital in protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The number of water molecules that interact with a protein at any given time is huge and each one has a large number of degrees of freedom and interaction partners.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Instead, protein design programs model most of such water molecules as a continuum, modeling both the hydrophobic effect and solvation polarization.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Individual water molecules can sometimes have a crucial structural role in the core of proteins, and in protein–protein or protein–ligand interactions.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Failing to model such waters can result in mispredictions of the optimal sequence of a protein–protein interface.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] As an alternative, water molecules can be added to rotamers.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The goal of protein design is to find a protein sequence that will fold to a target structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] A protein design algorithm must, thus, search all the conformations of each sequence, with respect to the target fold, and rank sequences according to the lowest-energy conformation of each one, as determined by the protein design energy function.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, a typical input to the protein design algorithm is the target fold, the sequence space, the structural flexibility, and the energy function, while the output is one or more sequences that are predicted to fold stably to the target structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The number of candidate protein sequences, however, grows exponentially with the number of protein residues; for example, there are 20100 protein sequences of length 100.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Furthermore, even if amino acid side-chain conformations are limited to a few rotamers (see Structural flexibility), this results in an exponential number of conformations for each sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, in our 100 residue protein, and assuming that each amino acid has exactly 10 rotamers, a search algorithm that searches this space will have to search over 200100 protein conformations.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The most common energy functions can be decomposed into pairwise terms between rotamers and amino acid types, which casts the problem as a combinatorial one, and powerful optimization algorithms can be used to solve it.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In those cases, the total energy of each conformation belonging to each sequence can be formulated as a sum of individual and pairwise terms between residue positions.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] If a designer is interested only in the best sequence, the protein design algorithm only requires the lowest-energy conformation of the lowest-energy sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In these cases, the amino acid identity of each rotamer can be ignored and all rotamers belonging to different amino acids can be treated the same.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Let *r**i* be a rotamer at residue position *i* in the protein chain, and *E*(*r**i*) the potential energy between the internal atoms of the rotamer.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Let *E*(*r**i*, *r**j*) be the potential energy between *r**i* and rotamer *r**j* at residue position *j*.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The problem of minimizing *ET* is an NP-hard problem.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Even though the class of problems is NP-hard, in practice many instances of protein design can be solved exactly or optimized satisfactorily through heuristic methods.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Several algorithms have been developed specifically for the protein design problem.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Exact algorithms guarantee that the optimization process produced the optimal according to the protein design model.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, if the predictions of exact algorithms fail when these are experimentally validated, then the source of error can be attributed to the energy function, the allowed flexibility, the sequence space or the target structure (e.g., if it cannot be designed for).
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Some protein design algorithms are listed below.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] For example, Rosetta Design incorporates sophisticated energy terms, and backbone flexibility using Monte Carlo as the underlying optimizing algorithm.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] OSPREY's algorithms build on the dead-end elimination algorithm and A* to incorporate continuous backbone and side-chain movements.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, these algorithms provide a good perspective on the different kinds of algorithms available for protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In 2020 scientists reported the development of an AI-based process using genome databases for evolution-based designing of novel proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] They used deep learning to identify design-rules.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In 2022, a study reported deep learning software that can design proteins that contain pre-specified functional sites.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The dead-end elimination (DEE) algorithm reduces the search space of the problem iteratively by removing rotamers that can be provably shown to be not part of the global lowest energy conformation (GMEC).
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Other powerful extensions to the dead-end elimination algorithm include the pairs elimination criterion, and the generalized dead-end elimination criterion.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] This algorithm has also been extended to handle continuous rotamers with provable guarantees.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Although the Dead-end elimination algorithm runs in polynomial time on each iteration, it cannot guarantee convergence.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] If, after a certain number of iterations, the dead-end elimination algorithm does not prune any more rotamers, then either rotamers have to be merged or another search algorithm must be used to search the remaining search space.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In such cases, the dead-end elimination acts as a pre-filtering algorithm to reduce the search space, while other algorithms, such as A*, Monte Carlo, Linear Programming, or FASTER are used to search the remaining search space.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The protein design conformational space can be represented as a tree, where the protein residues are ordered in an arbitrary way, and the tree branches at each of the rotamers in a residue.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Branch and bound algorithms use this representation to efficiently explore the conformation tree: At each *branching*, branch and bound algorithms *bound* the conformation space and explore only the promising branches.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] A popular search algorithm for protein design is the A* search algorithm.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] A* computes a lower-bound score on each partial tree path that lower bounds (with guarantees) the energy of each of the expanded rotamers.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Each partial conformation is added to a priority queue and at each iteration the partial path with the lowest lower bound is popped from the queue and expanded.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The algorithm stops once a full conformation has been enumerated and guarantees that the conformation is the optimal.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The A* score *f* in protein design consists of two parts, *f=g+h*.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] *g* is the exact energy of the rotamers that have already been assigned in the partial conformation.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] *h* is a lower bound on the energy of the rotamers that have not yet been assigned.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Each is designed as follows, where *d* is the index of the last assigned residue in the partial conformation.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The problem of optimizing *ET* (Equation (**1**)) can be easily formulated as an integer linear program (ILP).
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] ILP solvers, such as CPLEX, can compute the exact optimal solution for large instances of protein design problems.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] These solvers use a linear programming relaxation of the problem, where *qi* and *qij* are allowed to take continuous values, in combination with a branch and cut algorithm to search only a small portion of the conformation space for the optimal solution.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] ILP solvers have been shown to solve many instances of the side-chain placement problem.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] ILP solvers depend on linear programming (LP) algorithms, such as the Simplex or barrier-based methods to perform the LP relaxation at each branch.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] These LP algorithms were developed as general-purpose optimization methods and are not optimized for the protein design problem (Equation (**1**)).
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In consequence, the LP relaxation becomes the bottleneck of ILP solvers when the problem size is large.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Recently, several alternatives based on message-passing algorithms have been designed specifically for the optimization of the LP relaxation of the protein design problem.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Message-passing based approximations include the *tree reweighted max-product message passing* algorithm, and the *message passing linear programming* algorithm.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Monte Carlo is one of the most widely used algorithms for protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In its simplest form, a Monte Carlo algorithm selects a residue at random, and in that residue a randomly chosen rotamer (of any amino acid) is evaluated.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] where *β* is the Boltzmann constant and the temperature *T* can be chosen such that in the initial rounds it is high and it is slowly annealed to overcome local minima.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The FASTER algorithm uses a combination of deterministic and stochastic criteria to optimize amino acid sequences.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] FASTER first uses DEE to eliminate rotamers that are not part of the optimal solution.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Then, a series of iterative steps optimize the rotamer assignment.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In belief propagation for protein design, the algorithm exchanges messages that describe the *belief* that each residue has about the probability of each rotamer in neighboring residues.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The algorithm updates messages on every iteration and iterates until convergence or until a fixed number of iterations.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Convergence is not guaranteed in protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Both max-product and sum-product belief propagation have been used to optimize protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The design of new enzymes is a use of protein design with huge bioengineering and biomedical applications.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In general, designing a protein structure can be different from designing an enzyme, because the design of enzymes must consider many states involved in the catalytic mechanism.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] However protein design is a prerequisite of *de novo* enzyme design because, at the very least, the design of catalysts requires a scaffold in which the catalytic mechanism can be inserted.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Great progress in *de novo* enzyme design, and redesign, was made in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In three major studies, David Baker and coworkers *de novo* designed enzymes for the retro-aldol reaction, a Kemp-elimination reaction, and for the Diels-Alder reaction.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Furthermore, Stephen Mayo and coworkers developed an iterative method to design the most efficient known enzyme for the Kemp-elimination reaction.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Semi-rational design is a purposeful modification method based on a certain understanding of the sequence, structure, and catalytic mechanism of enzymes.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] This method is between irrational design and rational design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] It uses known information and means to perform evolutionary modification on the specific functions of the target enzyme.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The characteristic of semi-rational design is that it does not rely solely on random mutation and screening, but combines the concept of directed evolution.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] It creates a library of random mutants with diverse sequences through mutagenesis, error-prone RCR, DNA recombination, and site-saturation mutagenesis.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] At the same time, it uses the understanding of enzymes and design principles to purposefully screen out mutants with desired characteristics.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The methodology of semi-rational design emphasizes the in-depth understanding of enzymes and the control of the evolutionary process.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] It allows researchers to use known information to guide the evolutionary process, thereby improving efficiency and success rate.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] This method plays an important role in protein function modification because it can combine the advantages of irrational design and rational design, and can explore unknown space and use known knowledge for targeted modification.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Semi-rational design has a wide range of applications, including but not limited to enzyme optimization, modification of drug targets, evolution of biocatalysts, etc.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Through this method, researchers can more effectively improve the functional properties of proteins to meet specific biotechnology or medical needs.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Although this method has high requirements for information and technology and is relatively difficult to implement, with the development of computing technology and bioinformatics, the application prospects of semi-rational design in protein engineering are becoming more and more broad.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein–protein interactions are involved in most biotic processes.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Many of the hardest-to-treat diseases, such as Alzheimer's disease, many forms of cancer (e.g., TP53), and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection involve protein–protein interactions.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, to treat such diseases, it is desirable to design protein or protein-like therapeutics that bind one of the partners of the interaction and, thus, disrupt the disease-causing interaction.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] This requires designing protein-therapeutics for *affinity* toward its partner.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein–protein interactions can be designed using protein design algorithms because the principles that rule protein stability also rule protein–protein binding.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein–protein interaction design, however, presents challenges not commonly present in protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] One of the most important challenges is that, in general, the interfaces between proteins are more polar than protein cores, and binding involves a tradeoff between desolvation and hydrogen bond formation.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] To overcome this challenge, Bruce Tidor and coworkers developed a method to improve the affinity of antibodies by focusing on electrostatic contributions.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] They found that, for the antibodies designed in the study, reducing the desolvation costs of the residues in the interface increased the affinity of the binding pair.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The K* algorithm approximates the binding constant of the algorithm by including conformational entropy into the free energy calculation.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The design of protein–protein interactions must be highly specific because proteins can interact with a large number of proteins; successful design requires selective binders.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Thus, protein design algorithms must be able to distinguish between on-target (or *positive design*) and off-target binding (or *negative design*).
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] One of the most prominent examples of design for specificity is the design of specific bZIP-binding peptides by Amy Keating and coworkers for 19 out of the 20 bZIP families; 8 of these peptides were specific for their intended partner over competing peptides.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Further, positive and negative design was also used by Anderson and coworkers to predict mutations in the active site of a drug target that conferred resistance to a new drug; positive design was used to maintain wild-type activity, while negative design was used to disrupt binding of the drug.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Recent computational redesign by Costas Maranas and coworkers was also capable of experimentally switching the cofactor specificity of *Candida boidinii* xylose reductase from NADPH to NADH.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein resurfacing consists of designing a protein's surface while preserving the overall fold, core, and boundary regions of the protein intact.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Protein resurfacing is especially useful to alter the binding of a protein to other proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] One of the most important applications of protein resurfacing was the design of the RSC3 probe to select broadly neutralizing HIV antibodies at the NIH Vaccine Research Center.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] First, residues outside of the binding interface between the gp120 HIV envelope protein and the formerly discovered b12-antibody were selected to be designed.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Then, the sequence spaced was selected based on evolutionary information, solubility, similarity with the wild-type, and other considerations.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Then the RosettaDesign software was used to find optimal sequences in the selected sequence space.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] RSC3 was later used to discover the broadly neutralizing antibody VRC01 in the serum of a long-term HIV-infected non-progressor individual.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Globular proteins are proteins that contain a hydrophobic core and a hydrophilic surface.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Globular proteins often assume a stable structure, unlike fibrous proteins, which have multiple conformations.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The three-dimensional structure of globular proteins is typically easier to determine through X-ray crystallography and nuclear magnetic resonance than both fibrous proteins and membrane proteins, which makes globular proteins more attractive for protein design than the other types of proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Most successful protein designs have involved globular proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Both RSD-1, and Top7 were *de novo* designs of globular proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Five more protein structures were designed, synthesized, and verified in 2012 by the Baker group.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] These new proteins serve no biotic function, but the structures are intended to act as building-blocks that can be expanded to incorporate functional active sites.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] The structures were found computationally by using new heuristics based on analyzing the connecting loops between parts of the sequence that specify secondary structures.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Several transmembrane proteins have been successfully designed, along with many other membrane-associated peptides and proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Recently, Costas Maranas and his coworkers developed an automated tool to redesign the pore size of Outer Membrane Porin Type-F (OmpF) from *E.coli* to any desired sub-nm size and assembled them in membranes to perform precise angstrom scale separation.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] One of the most desirable uses for protein design is for biosensors, proteins that will sense the presence of specific compounds.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] Some attempts in the design of biosensors include sensors for unnatural molecules including TNT.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] More recently, Kuhlman and coworkers designed a biosensor of the PAK1.
[src:protein-design-computational/protein-design] In a sense, protein design is a subset of battery design.
[src:protein-design-computational/rational-design] This can be done either from scratch or by making calculated variations on a known structure, and usually complements directed evolution.
[src:protein-design-computational/rational-design] As an example, rational design is used to decipher collagen stability, mapping ligand-receptor interactions, unveiling protein folding and dynamics, and creating extra-biological structures by using fluorinated amino acids.
[src:protein-design-computational/rational-design] To treat cancer, rational design is used for targeted therapies where proteins are engineered to modify the communication of cells with their environment.
[src:protein-design-computational/rational-design] There is also the rational design of alfa-alkyl auxin molecules, which are auxin analogs capable of binding and blocking the formation of the hormone receptor complex.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Like all BOINC projects, Rosetta@home uses idle computer processing resources from volunteers' computers to perform calculations on individual workunits.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Completed results are sent to a central project server where they are validated and assimilated into project databases.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The project is cross-platform, and runs on a wide variety of hardware configurations.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Users can view the progress of their individual protein structure prediction on the Rosetta@home screensaver.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In addition to disease-related research, the Rosetta@home network serves as a testing framework for new methods in structural bioinformatics.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Such methods are then used in other Rosetta-based applications, like RosettaDock or the Human Proteome Folding Project and the Microbiome Immunity Project, after being sufficiently developed and proven stable on Rosetta@home's large and diverse set of volunteer computers.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta consistently ranks among the foremost docking predictors, and is one of the best tertiary structure predictors available.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] With an influx of new users looking to participate in the fight against the COVID-19 pandemic, caused by SARS-CoV-2, Rosetta@home increased its computing power up to 1.7 PetaFlops as of March 28, 2020.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] On September 9, 2020, Rosetta@home researchers published a paper describing 10 potent antiviral candidates against SARS-CoV-2.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home contributed to this research and these antiviral candidates are heading towards Phase 1 clinical trials, which may begin in early 2022.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] According to the Rosetta@home team, Rosetta volunteers contributed to the development of a nanoparticle vaccine.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This vaccine has been licensed and is known as the IVX-411 by Icosavax, which began a Phase I/II clinical trial in June 2021, and GBP510 which is being developed by SK Bioscience and is already approved for a Phase III clinical trial in South Korea.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] NL-201, a cancer drug candidate that was first created at the Institute of Protein Design (IPD) and published in a January 2019 paper, began a Phase 1 Human clinical trial in May 2021 with the support of Neoleukin Therapeutics, itself a spin-off from the IPD.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home played a role in the development of NL-201 and contributed with "forward folding" experiments that helped validate protein designs.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The Rosetta@home application and the BOINC volunteer computing platform are available for the operating systems Windows, Linux, and macOS; BOINC also runs on several others, e.g., FreeBSD.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Participation in Rosetta@home requires a central processing unit (CPU) with a clock speed of at least 500 MHz, 200 megabytes of free disk space, 512 megabytes of physical memory, and Internet connectivity.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] As of July 20, 2016, the current version of the Rosetta Mini application is 3.73.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The current recommended BOINC program version is 7.6.22.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Standard Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) (port 80) is used for communication between the user's BOINC client and the Rosetta@home servers at the University of Washington; HTTPS (port 443) is used during password exchange.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Remote and local control of the BOINC client use port 31416 and port 1043, which might need to be specifically unblocked if they are behind a firewall.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Workunits containing data on individual proteins are distributed from servers located in the Baker lab at the University of Washington to volunteers' computers, which then calculate a structure prediction for the assigned protein.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] To avoid duplicate structure predictions on a given protein, each workunit is initialized with a random seed number.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This gives each prediction a unique trajectory of descent along the protein's energy landscape.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Protein structure predictions from Rosetta@home are approximations of a global minimum in a given protein's energy landscape.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] That global minimum represents the most energetically favorable conformation of the protein, i.e., its native state.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] A primary feature of the Rosetta@home graphical user interface (GUI) is a screensaver which shows a current workunit's progress during the simulated protein folding process.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In the upper-left of the current screensaver, the target protein is shown adopting different shapes (conformations) in its search for the lowest energy structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Depicted immediately to the right is the structure of the most recently accepted.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] On the upper right the lowest energy conformation of the current decoy is shown; below that is the true, or native, structure of the protein if it has already been determined.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Three graphs are included in the screensaver.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Near the middle, a graph for the accepted model's thermodynamic free energy is displayed, which fluctuates as the accepted model changes.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] A graph of the accepted model's root-mean-square deviation (RMSD), which measures how structurally similar the accepted model is to the native model, is shown far right.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] On the right of the accepted energy graph and below the RMSD graph, the results from these two functions are used to produce an energy vs.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] RMSD plot as the model is progressively refined.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Like all BOINC projects, Rosetta@home runs in the background of the user's computer, using idle computer power, either at or before logging into an account on the host operating system.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The program frees resources from the CPU as they are needed by other applications so that normal computer use is unaffected.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] With the proliferation of genome sequencing projects, scientists can infer the amino acid sequence, or primary structure, of many proteins that carry out functions within the cell.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] To better understand a protein's function and aid in rational drug design, scientists need to know the protein's three-dimensional tertiary structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Protein 3D structures are currently determined experimentally via X-ray crystallography or nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The process is slow (it can take weeks or even months to figure out how to crystallize a protein for the first time) and costly (around US$100,000 per protein).
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] One of the main goals of Rosetta@home is to predict protein structures with the same accuracy as existing methods, but in a way that requires significantly less time and money.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Progress in protein structure prediction is evaluated in the biannual Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction (CASP) experiment, in which researchers from around the world attempt to derive a protein's structure from the protein's amino acid sequence.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] High scoring groups in this sometimes competitive experiment are considered the *de facto* standard-bearers for what is the state of the art in protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta, the program on which Rosetta@home is based, has been used since CASP5 in 2002.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In the 2004 CASP6 experiment, Rosetta made history by being the first to produce a close to atomic-level resolution, *ab initio protein structure prediction* in its submitted model for CASP target T0281.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] *Ab initio* modeling is considered an especially difficult category of protein structure prediction, as it does not use information from structural homology and must rely on information from sequence homology and modeling physical interactions within the protein.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home has been used in CASP since 2006, where it was among the top predictors in every category of structure prediction in CASP7.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] These high quality predictions were enabled by the computing power made available by Rosetta@home volunteers.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Increasing computing power allows Rosetta@home to sample more regions of conformation space (the possible shapes a protein can assume), which, according to Levinthal's paradox, is predicted to increase exponentially with protein length.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta is also used in protein–protein docking prediction, which determines the structure of multiple complexed proteins, or quaternary structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This type of protein interaction affects many cellular functions, including antigen–antibody and enzyme–inhibitor binding and cellular import and export.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Determining these interactions is critical for drug design.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta is used in the Critical Assessment of Prediction of Interactions (CAPRI) experiment, which evaluates the state of the protein docking field similar to how CASP gauges progress in protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The computing power made available by Rosetta@home's project volunteers has been cited as a major factor in Rosetta's performance in CAPRI 2007, where its docking predictions have been among the most accurate and complete.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In early 2008, Rosetta was used to computationally design a protein with a function never before observed in nature.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This was inspired in part by the retraction of a high-profile paper from 2004 which originally described the computational design of a protein with improved enzymatic activity relative to its natural form.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The 2008 research paper from David Baker's group describing how the protein was made, which cited Rosetta@home for the computing resources it made available, represented an important proof of concept for this protein design method.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This type of protein design could have future applications in drug discovery, green chemistry, and bioremediation.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The Rosetta computer program was cited in the 2024 Scientific Background to the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In addition to basic research in predicting protein structure, docking and design, Rosetta@home is also used in immediate disease-related research.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Numerous minor research projects are described in David Baker's Rosetta@home journal.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] As of February 2014, information on recent publications and a short description of the work are being updated on the forum.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The forum thread is no longer used since 2016, and news on the research can be found on the general news section of the project.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] A component of the Rosetta software suite, RosettaDesign, was used to accurately predict which regions of amyloidogenic proteins were most likely to make amyloid-like fibrils.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] By taking hexapeptides (six amino acid-long fragments) of a protein of interest and selecting the lowest energy match to a structure similar to that of a known fibril forming hexapeptide, RosettaDesign was able to identify peptides twice as likely to form fibrils as are random proteins.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home was used in the same study to predict structures for amyloid beta, a fibril-forming protein that has been postulated to cause Alzheimer's disease.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Preliminary but as yet unpublished results have been produced on Rosetta-designed proteins that may prevent fibrils from forming, although it is unknown whether it can prevent the disease.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Another component of Rosetta, RosettaDock, was used in conjunction with experimental methods to model interactions between three proteins—lethal factor (LF), edema factor (EF) and protective antigen (PA)—that make up anthrax toxin.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The computer model accurately predicted docking between LF and PA, helping to establish which domains of the respective proteins are involved in the LF–PA complex.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This insight was eventually used in research resulting in improved anthrax vaccines.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] RosettaDock was used to model docking between an antibody (immunoglobulin G) and a surface protein expressed by the cold sore virus, herpes simplex virus 1 (HSV-1) which serves to degrade the antiviral antibody.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The protein complex predicted by RosettaDock closely agreed with the especially difficult-to-obtain experimental models, leading researchers to conclude that the docking method has potential to address some of the problems that X-ray crystallography has with modelling protein–protein interfaces.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] As part of research funded by a $19.4 million grant by the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, Rosetta@home has been used in designing multiple possible vaccines for human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In research involved with the Grand Challenges in Global Health initiative, Rosetta has been used to computationally design novel homing endonuclease proteins, which could eradicate *Anopheles gambiae* or otherwise render the mosquito unable to transmit malaria.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Being able to model and alter protein–DNA interactions specifically, like those of homing endonucleases, gives computational protein design methods like Rosetta an important role in gene therapy (which includes possible cancer treatments).
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In 2020, the Rosetta molecular modelling suite was used to accurately predict the atomic-scale structure of the SARS-CoV-2 spike protein weeks before it could be measured in the lab.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] On June 26 of 2020, the project announced it had succeeded in creating antiviral proteins that neutralize SARS-CoV-2 virions in the lab and that these experimental antiviral drugs are being optimized for animal testing trials.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In a follow-up, a paper describing 10 SARS-CoV-2 miniprotein inhibitors was published in *Science* on September 9.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Two of these inhibitors, LCB1 and LCB3, are several times more potent than the best monoclonal antibodies being developed against SARS-CoV-2, both on a molar and mass basis.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In addition, the research suggests that these inhibitors retain their activity at elevated temperatures, are 20-fold smaller than an antibody and thus, have 20-fold more potential neutralizing sites, increasing the potential efficacy of a locally administered drug.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The small size and high stability of the inhibitors is expected to make them adequate to a gel formulation that can be nasally applied or as a powder to be administered directly onto the respiratory system.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The researchers will work on developing these inhibitors into therapeutics and prophylactics in the months ahead.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] As of July 2021, these antiviral candidates were forecasted to begin clinical trials in early 2022 and had received funding from the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation for preclinical and early clinical trials.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In animal testing trials, these antiviral candidates were effective against variants of concern including Alpha, Beta and Gamma.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home was used to help screen the over 2 million SARS-CoV-2 Spike-binding proteins that were computationally designed, and thus, contributed to this research.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Per the Rosetta@home team at the Institute of Protein Design, Rosetta@home volunteers contributed to the development of antiviral drug candidates and to a protein nanoparticle vaccine.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The IVX-411 vaccine is already on a Phase 1 clinical trial run by Icosavax while the same vaccine, licensed to another manufacturer and under the name GBP510, has been approved in South Korea for a Phase III trial run by SK Bioscience.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The candidate antivirals are also going towards Phase 1 clinical trials.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home researchers have designed an IL-2 receptor agonist called Neoleukin-2/15 that does not interact with the alpha subunit of the receptor.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Such immunity signal molecules are useful in cancer treatment.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] While the natural IL-2 suffers from toxicity due to an interaction with the alpha subunit, the designed protein is much safer, at least in animal models.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home contributed in "forward folding experiments" which helped validate designs.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In a September 2020 feature in the *New Yorker*, David Baker stated that Neoleukin-2/15 would begin human clinical trials "later this year".
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Neoleukin-2/15 is being developed by Neoleukin, a spin-off company from the Baker lab.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In December 2020, Neoleukin announced it would be submitting an Investigational New Drug application with the Food and Drug Administration in order to begin a Phase 1 clinical trial of NL-201, which is a further development of Neoleukin-2/15.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] A similar application was submitted in Australia and Neoleukin hopes to enrol up 120 participants on the Phase 1 clinical trial.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The Phase 1 human clinical trial began on May 5, 2021.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Originally introduced by the Baker laboratory at the University of Washington in 1998 as an *ab initio* approach to structure prediction, Rosetta has since branched into several development streams and distinct services, providing features such as macromolecular docking and protein design.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Many of the graduate students and other researchers involved in Rosetta's initial development have since moved to other universities and research institutions, and subsequently enhanced different parts of the Rosetta project.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The Rosetta platform derives its name from the Rosetta Stone, as it attempts to decipher the structural "meaning" of proteins' amino acid sequences.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Development of the Rosetta code is done by Rosetta Commons.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta was rewritten in C++ to allow easier development than that allowed by its original version, which was written in Fortran.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This new version is object-oriented, and was released to Rosetta@Home February 8, 2008.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] RosettaDesign, a computing approach to protein design based on Rosetta, began in 2000 with a study in redesigning the folding pathway of Protein G.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In 2002 RosettaDesign was used to design Top7, a 93-amino acid long α/β protein that had an overall fold never before recorded in nature.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This new conformation was predicted by Rosetta to within 1.2 Å RMSD of the structure determined by X-ray crystallography, representing an unusually accurate structure prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The visible product of that research, Top7, was featured as the RCSB PDB's 'Molecule of the Month' in October 2006; a superposition of the respective cores (residues 60–79) of its predicted and X-ray crystal structures are featured in the Rosetta@home logo.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Brian Kuhlman, a former postdoctoral associate in David Baker's lab and now an associate professor at the University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, offers RosettaDesign as an online service.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] RosettaDock was added to the Rosetta software suite during the first CAPRI experiment in 2002 as the Baker laboratory's algorithm for protein–protein docking prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In that experiment, RosettaDock made a high-accuracy prediction for the docking between streptococcal pyogenic exotoxin A and a T cell-receptor β-chain, and a medium accuracy prediction for a complex between porcine α-amylase and a camelid antibody.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] While the RosettaDock method only made two acceptably accurate predictions out of seven possible, this was enough to rank it seventh out of nineteen prediction methods in the first CAPRI assessment.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Development of RosettaDock diverged into two branches for subsequent CAPRI rounds as Jeffrey Gray, who laid the groundwork for RosettaDock while at the University of Washington, continued working on the method in his new position at Johns Hopkins University.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Members of the Baker laboratory further developed RosettaDock in Gray's absence.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The two versions differed slightly in side-chain modeling, decoy selection and other areas.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Despite these differences, both the Baker and Gray methods performed well in the second CAPRI assessment, placing fifth and seventh respectively out of 30 predictor groups.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Jeffrey Gray's RosettaDock server is available as a free docking prediction service for non-commercial use.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In October 2006, RosettaDock was integrated into Rosetta@home.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The method used a fast, crude docking model phase using only the protein backbone.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This was followed by a slow full-atom refinement phase in which the orientation of the two interacting proteins relative to each other, and side-chain interactions at the protein–protein interface, were simultaneously optimized to find the lowest energy conformation.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The vastly increased computing power afforded by the Rosetta@home network, combined with revised *fold-tree* representations for backbone flexibility and loop modeling, made RosettaDock sixth out of 63 prediction groups in the third CAPRI assessment.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The Robetta (Rosetta Beta) server is an automated protein structure prediction service offered by the Baker laboratory for non-commercial *ab initio* and comparative modeling.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] It has participated as an automated prediction server in the biannual CASP experiments since CASP5 in 2002, performing among the best in the automated server prediction category.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Robetta has since competed in CASP6 and 7, where it did better than average among both automated server and human predictor groups.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] It also participates in the CAMEO3D continuous evaluation.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Robetta tasks run on Baker lab servers, Janelia Research Campus machines, and Rosetta@home participant computers.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Domains with structural homologs then follow a "template-based model" (i.e., homology modeling) protocol.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Here, the Baker laboratory's in-house alignment program, K*sync, produces a group of sequence homologs, and each of these is modeled by the Rosetta *de novo* method to produce a decoy (possible structure).
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The final structure prediction is selected by taking the lowest energy model as determined by a low-resolution Rosetta energy function.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] For domains that have no detected structural homologs, a *de novo* protocol is followed in which the lowest energy model from a set of generated decoys is selected as the final prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] These domain predictions are then connected together to investigate inter-domain, tertiary-level interactions within the protein.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Finally, side-chain contributions are modeled using a protocol for Monte Carlo conformational search.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In CASP8, Robetta was augmented to use Rosetta's high resolution all-atom refinement method, the absence of which was cited as the main cause for Robetta being less accurate than the Rosetta@home network in CASP7.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In CASP11, a way to predict the protein contact map by co-evolution of residues in related proteins called GREMLIN was added, allowing for more *de novo* fold successes.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta is available as an online service from a number of other public servers.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] ROSIE offers a variety of functions from RNA structure prediction and design to ligand docking and antibody modeling.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] On May 9, 2008, after Rosetta@home users suggested an interactive version of the volunteer computing program, the Baker lab publicly released Foldit, an online protein structure prediction game based on the Rosetta platform.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] As of September 25, 2008, Foldit had over 59,000 registered users.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The game gives users a set of controls (for example, shake, wiggle, rebuild) to manipulate the backbone and amino acid side chains of the target protein into more energetically favorable conformations.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Users can work on solutions individually as *soloists* or collectively as *evolvers*, accruing points under either category as they improve their structure predictions.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Foldit can work as a GUI frontend to Rosetta under a tailored "professional mode".
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] RoseTTAFold, which is inspired by AlphaFold, uses a neural network to predict the distance and orientation between residues.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] These predictions guide Rosetta software in producing a structure.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] RoseTTAFold is open source under the MIT license.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The Jianyi Yang lab in China offers a modified version of Rosetta termed tr-RosettaX2 (transform-restrained Rosetta).
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] It uses a deep learning-based contact prediction method different from RoseTTAFold to guide the usual Rosetta folding algorithm. trRosetta predates RoseTTAFold.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Of all the major volunteer computing projects involved in protein research, Folding@home is the only one not using the BOINC platform.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Both Rosetta@home and Folding@home study protein misfolding diseases such as Alzheimer's disease, but Folding@home does so much more exclusively.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Folding@home almost exclusively uses all-atom molecular dynamics models to understand how and why proteins fold (or potentially misfold, and subsequently aggregate to cause diseases).
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] In other words, Folding@home's strength is modeling the process of protein folding, while Rosetta@home's strength is computing protein design and predicting protein structure and docking.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Some of Rosetta@home's results are used as the basis for some Folding@home projects.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta provides the most likely structure, but it is not definite if that is the form the molecule takes or whether or not it is viable.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Folding@home can then be used to verify Rosetta@home's results, and can provide added atomic-level information, and details of how the molecule changes shape.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The two projects also differ significantly in their computing power and host diversity.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Averaging about 6,650 teraFLOPS from a host base of central processing units (CPUs), graphics processing units (GPUs), and (formerly) PS3s, Folding@home has nearly 108 times more computing power than Rosetta@home.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Both Phase I and Phase II of the Human Proteome Folding Project (HPF), a subproject of World Community Grid, have used the Rosetta program to make structural and functional annotations of various genomes.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Although he now uses it to create databases for biologists, Richard Bonneau, head scientist of the Human Proteome Folding Project, was active in the original development of Rosetta at David Baker's laboratory while obtaining his PhD.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] More information on the relationship between the HPF1, HPF2 and Rosetta@home can be found on Richard Bonneau's website.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Like Rosetta@home, Predictor@home specialized in protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] While Rosetta@home uses the Rosetta program for its structure prediction, Predictor@home used the dTASSER methodology.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Other protein related volunteer computing projects on BOINC include QMC@home, Docking@home, POEM@home, SIMAP, and TANPAKU.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] RALPH@home, the Rosetta@home alpha project which tests new application versions, work units, and updates before they move on to Rosetta@home, runs on BOINC also.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home depends on computing power donated by individual project members for its research.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] As of March 28, 2020, about 53,000 users from 150 countries were active members of Rosetta@home, together contributing idle processor time from about 54,800 computers for a combined average performance of over 1.7 PetaFLOPS.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Users are granted BOINC credits as a measure of their contribution.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The credit granted for each workunit is the number of decoys produced for that workunit multiplied by the average claimed credit for the decoys submitted by all computer hosts for that workunit.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] This custom system was designed to address significant differences between credit granted to users with the standard BOINC client and an optimized BOINC client, and credit differences between users running Rosetta@home on Windows and Linux operating systems.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] The amount of credit granted per second of CPU work is lower for Rosetta@home than most other BOINC projects.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home is thirteenth out of over 40 BOINC projects in terms of total credit.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Rosetta@home users who predict protein structures submitted for the CASP experiment are acknowledged in scientific publications regarding their results.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] Users who predict the lowest energy structure for a given workunit are featured on the Rosetta@home homepage as *Predictor of the Day*, along with any team of which they are a member.
[src:protein-design-computational/rosetta-home] A *User of the Day* is chosen randomly each day to be on the homepage also, from among users who have made a Rosetta@home profile.
